==English==
===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|ˈpɹʌ.ʃə}}, {{IPA|ˈpɹuːsiːə}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ʌʃə|-ʌʃə]]

===Etymology===
From the New Latin 'Prussia'<!-- NOTE: not 'Borussia', which is archaicised Latin, and, while entirely nice, is not relevant to the etymology of this word -->, the Latin form used by Peter of Dusburg for the name of the region in the now-extinct language of its Baltic inhabitants, '[[Prūsa]]'.

===Proper noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''Prussia'''
# A geographical area on the Baltic coast of northeastern Europe.
# A former Baltic country, annihilated by the [[w:Teutonic Order|Teutonic Order]] and absorbed by Germany.
# A German province that was the predecessor to, and a member of, the [[w:German Empire|German Empire]]; erased at the end of the Second World War.

===Usage notes===
Linguistic evidence affirms that the name is pronounced with a long ''u'' : {{IPA|ˈpɹuːsiːə}}.  (Such is the pronounciation of the equivalent terms in [[w:Old Prussian language|Prussian]] and [[w:German language|German]], and such was the only pronunciation in [[W:Middle English|Middle English]].)  Anglicised pronunciation, with a short ''u'' ({{IPA|ˈpɹʌ.ʃə}}), is also common in modern English, however.

